I"t<h1 class="fs-8" id="tropy">Tropy</h1>

<p class="fs-5 fw-300">A free, open-source tool for organizing and describing your archival research photos.</p>

<hr />

<h2 id="what-is-it-good-for">What is It Good For?</h2>

<p>Trying to keep track of archival materials can be a challenge. You came back from the archive with 600 photos on your phone or camera. They have meaningless filenames like <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">IMG_4392.jpg</code>. You sort of remember what‚Äôs in them, but finding that one letter from 1847 means scrolling through hundreds of images. Tropy lets you organize, describe, and annotate those photos so you can actually <em>find</em> things.</p>

<p><strong>Where it fits in the workflow:</strong> Search ‚Üí Collect ‚Üí Organize ‚Üí Read &amp; Analyze ‚Üí Write &amp; Cite</p>

<hr />

<h2 id="get-started-45-minute-path">Get started (45-minute path)</h2>

<h3 id="1-install-tropy-3-min">1. Install Tropy (3 min)</h3>

<p>Tropy is a desktop application, which means that you have to install it and run it locally on your machine rather than accessing it through an internet browser.</p>

<blockquote>
  <p><strong>Note:</strong> If you‚Äôre installing on workshop wifi alongside other participants, the download may take longer than expected. Flag Brady if you get stuck.</p>
</blockquote>

<ul>
  <li>Go to <a href="https://tropy.org/">tropy.org</a> and download the version for your operating system</li>
  <li>Install and open it</li>
</ul>

<h3 id="2-create-a-project-2-min">2. Create a project (2 min)</h3>

<ul>
  <li>Go to File ‚Üí New ‚Üí Project</li>
  <li>Name it after your research project or the archive you visited</li>
  <li>Choose where to save the project file (<code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">.tpy</code>)‚Äîkeep it somewhere you won‚Äôt lose it</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Key concept:</strong> A Tropy project is a database that <em>points to</em> your photos. It doesn‚Äôt move or copy the photos themselves. So make sure your photos are in a stable location before you start (don‚Äôt leave them on a USB drive you might unplug).</p>

<h3 id="3-import-photos-5-min">3. Import photos (5 min)</h3>

<ul>
  <li>Drag and drop a folder of photos into Tropy, or go to File ‚Üí Import ‚Üí Photos</li>
  <li>Start with a manageable batch‚Äî20‚Äì30 images is plenty for today</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Note:</strong> If you don‚Äôt have archival photos handy, download a small set of sample images from a digital archive like the <a href="https://www.loc.gov/collections/">Library of Congress Digital Collections</a> or <a href="https://archive.org/">Internet Archive</a>.</p>

<h3 id="4-understand-items-vs-photos-5-min">4. Understand items vs. photos (5 min)</h3>

<p>This is Tropy‚Äôs most important concept:</p>

<ul>
  <li>A <strong>photo</strong> is a single image file</li>
  <li>An <strong>item</strong> is a <em>thing</em> in the archive‚Äîa letter, a diary entry, a document‚Äîthat might span multiple photos</li>
</ul>

<p>If you photographed a 4-page letter, that‚Äôs 4 photos but 1 item. To merge photos into one item:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Select the photos in the item view</li>
  <li>Right-click ‚Üí Merge selected items</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Exercise:</strong> Find a few photos that belong together and merge them into a single item.</p>

<h3 id="5-add-metadata-15-min">5. Add metadata (15 min)</h3>

<p>Select an item and look at the metadata panel on the right. The default template gives you fields like:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Title</strong>‚Äîwhat is this? (‚ÄúLetter from Jane Smith to Mary Jones‚Äù)</li>
  <li><strong>Date</strong>‚Äîwhen was it created?</li>
  <li><strong>Creator</strong>‚Äîwho made it?</li>
  <li><strong>Archive / Collection</strong>‚Äîwhere did you find it?</li>
  <li><strong>Rights</strong>‚Äîany access or usage restrictions?</li>
</ul>

<p>You don‚Äôt need to fill in every field. Focus on the information that will help you <em>find this item later</em>.</p>

<p><strong>Exercise:</strong> Add metadata to at least 5 items. Start with Title and Date‚Äîthose two fields alone will transform your ability to search.</p>

<h3 id="6-use-tags-and-notes-10-min">6. Use tags and notes (10 min)</h3>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Tags:</strong> In the tag panel, add descriptive tags to your items (e.g., ‚Äúcorrespondence,‚Äù ‚Äúfinancial records,‚Äù ‚Äúmentions-labor‚Äù). Tags work like tags in Zotero or similar information organization systems‚Äîthey let you filter across your whole project.</li>
  <li><strong>Notes:</strong> Select a photo within an item, then use the notes panel to transcribe text, jot observations, or record questions. Notes are searchable.</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>A note on tagging as interpretation:</strong> The tags you choose are not neutral. Deciding that a document ‚Äúmentions-labor‚Äù or belongs to ‚Äúwomen‚Äôs networks‚Äù or represents ‚Äústate violence‚Äù reflects your analytical framework ‚Äî it‚Äôs an early act of interpretation, not just a filing decision. The schema you develop in Tropy is, in a real sense, a draft argument about what matters in your archive and how things relate to each other. Take it seriously: your tagging vocabulary is part of your methodology.</p>

<p><strong>Exercise:</strong> Tag your items with at least 2‚Äì3 tags each. Try to use at least one tag that describes the document‚Äôs <em>content or type</em> (e.g., ‚Äúcorrespondence,‚Äù ‚Äúfinancial record‚Äù) and one that describes its <em>relationship to your argument</em> (e.g., ‚Äúlabor-organizing,‚Äù ‚Äúcounters-my-thesis,‚Äù ‚Äúkey-evidence‚Äù). Add a note to one item.</p>

<h3 id="7-use-selections-optional--if-you-finish-early">7. Use selections (optional ‚Äî if you finish early)</h3>

<p>Selections let you highlight a region of a photo ‚Äî useful for marking a specific paragraph, a signature, a stamp, or an annotation within a larger page.</p>

<ul>
  <li>Open an item‚Äôs photo in the main viewer</li>
  <li>Click and drag to draw a rectangle around the area of interest</li>
  <li>The selection appears as a sub-item you can add its own notes and tags to</li>
</ul>

<hr />

<h2 id="tips-for-long-term-success">Tips for long-term success</h2>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Describe as you go.</strong> It‚Äôs much harder to remember what things are three months after the archive trip. Even a quick title is better than nothing.</li>
  <li><strong>Develop a consistent tagging vocabulary.</strong> Write down the tags you‚Äôre using and what they mean. You‚Äôll thank yourself when the project grows.</li>
  <li><strong>Use Tropy‚Äôs export</strong> to generate JSON-LD or CSV files if you need to work with your metadata in other tools.</li>
</ul>

